You're facing an issue with event listeners in JavaScript, and you're concerned about manually defining each event listener for each star. 

This is a common problem when dealing with multiple elements and event listeners. Here are a few solutions to help you avoid manually defining each event listener:

### 1. Use a loop to add event listeners

If you have a fixed number of stars, you can use a loop to add event listeners. This way, you don't have to manually define each event listener.

```javascript
const stars = document.querySelectorAll('.star');

stars.forEach((star, index) => {
  star.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log(`Star ${index + 1} clicked`);
  });
});
```

### 2. Use a single event listener on a container element

If your stars are contained within a single element, you can add a single event listener to that container element. Then, use event delegation to determine which star was clicked.

```javascript
const starContainer = document.querySelector('.star-container');

starContainer.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
  const star = event.target.closest('.star');
  if (star) {
    console.log(`Star clicked: ${star.dataset.index}`);
  }
});
```

